{\\line{\\pard\\ql\\ul\\fo\\fs22 NOTE: \\par}\\pard\\plain\\fo\\fs22 There is no revision service for this manual. The operator is responsible for updating this manual to reflect the AIRCRAFT STATUS AFTER DELIVERY. A guideline for updating the manual is provided in the manual introduction.\\par\\page} {\\pard\\qc\\fo\\fs22 TABLE OF CONTENTS \\par\\line{\\pard\\plain\\ql\\f22\\fs16 Aucune entr\\'e9e de table des mati\\'e8res n'a \\'e9t\\'e9 trouv\\'e9e.\\par}\\page}{\\pard\\qc\\s255\\li360\\sb240\\sa240\\keepn\\ul\\b\\i\\f20\\fs22 INTRODUCTION \\par} {\\line\\pard\\ql\\ul\\f0\\fs22 1.General \\line\\par\\pard\\plain\\ql\\f0\\fs22 The Electrical Load Analysis (ELA) gives the necessary operational/maximum electrical loads of the various aircraft systems in the different flight phase configurations. \\line\\par\\pard\\ql\\fs22 The operator can use the ELA data to evaluate the effects of system modifications on electrical load distribution and power consumption.\\line\\par\\pard\\ql\\fs22 This ELA contains customized data that is applicable to the aircraft specified on the title page (A/C type and MSN) and reflects the \\b AIRCRAFT STATUS AT DELIVERY. \\plain AIRBUS does \\b not issue revisions \\plain for this manual \\line\\par} {\\pard\\ql\\fs22 The structure of the ELA is as follows \\line\\par} {\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\tab Introduction to the ELA and general description of the aircraft electrical network \\par} {\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\tab Electrical loads at busbar/sub-busbar level \\line\\tab This part gives the nominal power rating and the maximum and operational loads for each circuit breaker connected to the specified busbar/sub-busbar for the different flight phases. \\par} {\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\tab Electrical loads at generator and converter level \\line\\tab This part gives the breakdown of the busbar loads for each power source when power is supplied to the aircraft by all the Integrated Drive Generators and by only one IDG. An analysis is also provided per channel (side 1, side 2, and essential channel). \\par} {\\line\\pard\\plain\\f0\\fs22\\ql Guidelines for the validation of new electrical load installations and related update of the ELA are given in paragraph 3 of this introduction. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\plain\\f0\\fs22\\ql To get a customized diagram of the electrical power generation and distribution (AC/DC), refer to the applicable block diagram given in the Aircraft Schematic Manual (Ref. ASM 24-00-01). \\par}{\\pard\\ql\\fo\\fs22 \\ul Note: \\plain In the ASM, the effectivity statement is in Fleet Serial Number (FSN) and not in Manufacturer Serial Number (MSN). \\par} {\\line\\pard\\ql\\fs22\\ul 2. ELA document Presentation \\par} {\\line\\pard\\ql\\fs22\\tab \\ul 2.1. Electrical Load data \\par} {\\line\\pard\\ql\\fs22 Each circuit breaker is listed in the ELA with the data that follows: \\line\\par} {\\pard\\plain\\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900\\fs22\\endash\\b ELEC IDENT: \\plain\\fs22 Functional Item Number (FIN) of the circuit breaker \\par}{\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\b C: \\plain\\fs22 circuit breaker open with safety clip installed \\par}{\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\b PANEL: \\plain\\fs22 VU/VE electrical panel where the circuit breaker is located \\par}{\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\b ATA100: 4-digit: \\plain\\fs22 ATA reference of the system \\par}{\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\b DESIGNATION: \\plain\\fs22 designation of the circuit breaker \\par}{\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\b I: \\plain\\fs22 Intermittent load \\par}{\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\b NOMINAL POWER: \\plain\\fs22 maximum design power consumption of the system connected to the circuit breaker \\par}{\\pard\\plain \\s4\\fi-280\\li900\\sa120\\tx900 \\fs22 \\endash \\b Flight Phases: \\plain\\fs22 power consumption of the system connected to the circuit breaker for each flight phase \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\tab \\ul 2.2. Flight phase definition \\par} {\\pard\\ql\\fs22 The flight phases of a typical A318/A319/A320/A321 flight are as follows: \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Ground: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab Engines stopped \\line\\tab\\tab\\tab Ground power unit(s) or/and APU generator on-line or ground service \\line\\tab\\tab\\tab Configuration \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Start: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab Start of the engines \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Roll: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab Taxi lights on, roll, engines at idle, braking sequence, roll. \\line\\tab\\tab\\tab The end of this phase is when the landing gear is no longer compressed \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Take-off: \\plain\\fs22\\tab From the moment the landing gear is no longer compressed to a height of 1500 ft \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Climb: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab From 1500 ft to a stabilized level \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Cruise: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab Stabilized level at which the major part of the flight is performed \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Descent: \\plain\\fs22\\tab From a stabilized level to 800ft \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Landing: \\plain\\fs22\\tab From start of landing procedure to touchdown \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\b Taxiing: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab From touchdown to engine shutdown \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\tab \\ul 2.3. Load Definition \\par\\line} {\\pard\\fs22\\tab\\tab \\ul 2.3.1. Maximum, operational and nominal loads \\par} {\\line\\pard\\ql\\fs22 The maximum, operational and nominal load values are defined as follows: \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\b MAXI: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab Most probable power consumption in the most unfavorable conditions. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\b OPEARTIONAL: \\plain\\fs22\\tab Most probable power consumption in normal operating conditions. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\b NOMINAL: \\plain\\fs22\\tab\\tab Maximum design power consumption of the specified system. \\par\\page} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\tab\\tab \\ul 2.3.2. Intermittent loads \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 The intermittent loads are related to systems that have a power consumption of short duration. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\tab \\ul 2.4. Electrical load breakdown \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\tab\\tab \\ul 2.4.1. Electrical loads at busbar/sub-busbar level \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 The busbar/sub-busbar loads are the arithmetical sum of the associated circuit breaker loads. The power consumption is given in VA for AC loads and W for DC loads. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 For each busbar/sub-busbar, two tables, one for Maximum and one for Operational, give: \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\b - BUSBAR - TOTAL NOT SHEDDABLE: \\plain\\fs22 Sum of all the consumer loads that are not shed by \\line automatic logic in degraded electrical configurations. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\b - BUSBAR - TOTAL: \\plain\\fs22 Sum of all the consumer loads. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\tab\\tab \\ul 2.4.2. Electrical load at generator and converter level \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 The generator loads are the arithmetical sum of the related AC busbar/sub-busbar loads and converter loads. They are given in VA. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 For the converters, the conversion from W to VA uses the power factor and the efficiency of the TRU. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 The converter loads are the arithmetical sum of the associated DC busbar/sub-busbar loads. They are given in W. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 The total load on each generator and converter (arithmetical computation) is given at the end of the document. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 For each generator and converter, two tables, one for Maximum and one for Operational, give: \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\b - Total Load: \\plain\\fs22 Sum of all the consumer loads. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\b - NOT SHEDDABLE TOTAL LOAD: \\plain\\fs22 Sum of all the consumer loads not shed by \\line in degraded electrical configurations. \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\ul 3. Guidelines for validation of new electrical load installations and related ELA update \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22 The Methodology for validation of new electrical load installations and related ELA update is on AirbusWorld portal: \\par} {\\pard\\fs22\\b\\bullet\\plain\\tab\\fs22 From AirbusWorld home page, select \\"Customization & Delivery\\" \\par} {\\pard\\fs22\\b\\bullet\\plain\\tab\\fs22 At the bottom of the \\"Acceptance & Delivery\\" column, select \\"ELA - Electrical Load Analysis\\" \\par} {\\pard\\fs22\\b\\bullet\\plain\\tab\\fs22 Select your MSN and refer to the guideline available \\line\\tab in the dedicated tab (Methodology to update documents).\\par\\page}{\\pard\\s255\\li360\\sb240\\sa240\\keepn\\ul\\b\\i\\f20\\fs22\\qc ELECTRICAL LOAD DATA \\par} {\\line\\pard\\fs22\\ql The electrical load data are given in the following pages.\\par}\\sect}{\\sectd\\lndscpsxn\\paperw16833\\paperh11908\\margl720\\margr720\\margt720\\margb720\\headery284\\footery0
